ðərɪn]%0a%3c %0a%3c Generally, it seems that verbs that have been made into participles or gerunds are what gets g-dropped, but there are a couple examples such as "everything" and "something" that I recall many people in the South would replace with their g-dropped counterparts. There are some words that cannot be g-dropped. These would be words like "thing" (note that the compound words above contained this one) or "bring". For "thing", this makes sense as there is another word "thin", which would conflict with a g-dropped "thing". As for "bring", I think it may be un-droppable because, unlike a verb which has %3c-ing> appended, the %3cing> is part of what makes "bring" a word. In other words, a gerund-ized verb like "running" is still recognizable when g-dropped as "runnin'" because the root word is still there, whereas in "bring" there is no root word to be recognized in the g-dropped "brin'", thus making it sound like a whole other word.%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Sources:%0a%3c - https://jon-west-language.blogspot.com/2013/03/are-you-listenin-phenomenon-of-g.html%0a%3c - https://languagelog.ldc.upenn.edu/nll/?p=3520%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Expansions:%0a%3c [[#expansions]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#expansionsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%3c %0a%3c (:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:else:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%3c %0a%3c (:ifend:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c !!Comments%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c (:section: F:)%0a%3c (:Category: PhonologicalPhenomenaInSpokenLanguages:)%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
